# Allowlist for the public mirror.
#
# Lines starting with `#` and blank lines are ignored. Every other
# line is a path or path prefix passed to `git-filter-repo
# --paths-from-file`. Anything not matched is excluded from the
# mirror (fail-safe for new sensitive files).
#
# The starting set below contains the files commonly safe to ship.
# Add repo-specific paths below the marker. Audit additions
# carefully — paths NOT on this list are excluded, but paths that
# ARE on this list ship verbatim.
#
# Do NOT add the source repo's own root `.gitignore`, most of
# `.github/`, or `pull_request_template.md`:
# - `.github/workflows/public-mirror.yml` and the rest of
#   `.github/public-mirror/` are upstream-only plumbing. Including them
#   makes the workflow's force-push fail with "refusing to allow an
#   OAuth App to create or update workflow ... without `workflow`
#   scope" — deploy keys cannot write workflow files. The ONE exception
#   is `.github/public-mirror/gitignore.mirror`, which is selected AND
#   renamed to repo-root `.gitignore` by the rename directive at the
#   bottom of this file (see that comment).
# - The source repo's own root `.gitignore` must NOT ship: it un-ignores
#   paths that exist in the private repo but are deliberately EXCLUDED
#   from the mirror (memory/, output-styles/, plans/, designs/, the
#   nested .claude/, .github/), so a consumer's `git status` would
#   reference un-ignore rules for paths absent from their clone. The
#   mirror instead ships a distinct, hand-maintained `gitignore.mirror`
#   renamed in below (issue #208). Previously the workflow SYNTHESIZED a
#   `.gitignore` as a commit on top of filter-repo's output; that synth
#   commit sat outside filter-repo's `--state-branch` marks and made
#   every source-change run diverge from the prior mirror tip and
#   force-push, breaking consumers' `git pull`. Shipping it through
#   filter-repo (this rename) keeps the mirror fast-forwarding.
# - `pull_request_template.md` doesn't make sense to ship from the
#   source: the source's template (if any) would say "describe your
#   change", but the mirror needs a "PRs not accepted, go upstream"
#   message. One file can't serve both meanings. The mirror's
#   read-only banner lives in README.md and Issues are disabled at
#   the repo level, so a PR-template redirect isn't load-bearing.

# --- conventionally shipped (remove any you don't want public) ---
README.md
LICENSE
PATENTS
PRIOR_ART.md
CODEOWNERS
# Static informational file (no longer synthesized on top of
# filter-repo's output — issue #208). Shipped like any other path.
CONTRIBUTORS

# --- repo-specific (add below) ---
# Ships the self-contained install script; also the payload dir #151 populates.
.global-claude-config/
CLAUDE.md
agents/
skills/
rules/
hooks/
keybindings.json
settings.json

# --- mirror .gitignore: the ONE path under .github/ that survives ---
# This selects `.github/public-mirror/gitignore.mirror` AND renames it
# to repo-root `.gitignore` on the mirror. filter-repo's
# --paths-from-file consumes the `==>` rename directive inline, so no
# separate --path-rename flag is needed. NOTE: in the installed
# filter-repo version, a rename directive does NOT by itself select the
# source path — it selects *and* renames only when the source path is
# ALSO present as a plain selection line. We therefore list the source
# path on its own line first, then the rename directive. (Verified
# against the installed git-filter-repo; the bare `==>` directive alone
# left `.gitignore` absent from the output.)
#
# This is the only `.github/` path that ships: the rest of `.github/`
# (workflows, the rest of public-mirror/) is intentionally excluded as
# upstream-only plumbing. Shipping the mirror .gitignore through
# filter-repo (rather than synthesizing it as a commit on top) is what
# lets routine runs fast-forward instead of diverging (issue #208).
.github/public-mirror/gitignore.mirror
.github/public-mirror/gitignore.mirror==>.gitignore
